skirts</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../105/19150105.xml">
pants</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../337/185337.xml">
sweaters</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../178/27178.xml">
shoes</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../788/1949788.xml">
accessories</link> with clean silhouettes made of fine materials. Even though the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../180/38180.xml">
clothes</link> "have virtually no profile, in part because they are often intentionally nondescript" and are hence "almost impossible to identify"<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E1DD103DF937A35756C0A9629C8B63">
http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E1DD103DF937A35756C0A9629C8B63</weblink> the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../900/18950900.xml">
label</link> still attracts a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../588/1008588.xml">
cult</link>-like following amongst fashion conscious <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../818/7818.xml">
consumers</link>. Retail prices range from about $200 for blouses, shirts and pants to $300 for summer dresses and $500 for blazers, for example.</p>
