Lawsuit</st>
<p>

In 2006 Tahari <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../258/113258.xml">
sued</link> his former partner Rosen (as well as Link Theory Holdings and Mr. Sakasi) for having urged Tahari to sell <it>theory</it> at a price below its value to the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../573/15573.xml">
Japanese</link> in 2003, seeking <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../134/8134.xml">
damages</link> and a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../243/866243.xml">
share</link> in the proceeds from the company's <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../879/63879.xml">
IPO</link> in excess of $ 180 mio. Rosen had also said that he would <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../495/26495.xml">
retire</link> from the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../223/4918223.xml">
company</link> within a year from the sale when, in fact, after Tahari's departure, he stayed on as the newly established company's president. <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.nypost.com/seven/09072006/business/tahari_sues_ex_partner_business_suzanne_kapner.htm">
http://www.nypost.com/seven/09072006/business/tahari_sues_ex_partner_business_suzanne_kapner.htm</weblink> Link Theory called Mr. Tahari's complaint "frivolous claims" <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.link-theory.com/resources/3275/20060908IRPR-En.pdf">
http://www.link-theory.com/resources/3275/20060908IRPR-En.pdf</weblink>, Rosen labelled it "seller's remorse" <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.nypost.com/seven/06262007/business/split_seams_business_suzanne_kapner.htm">
http://www.nypost.com/seven/06262007/business/split_seams_business_suzanne_kapner.htm</weblink> and the case was later dismissed by a <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../042/645042.xml">
New York</link></village>
 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../719/44719.xml">
judge</link>, even denying Tahari's claim for unpaid royalties by <it>theory</it>'s then Asian <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../148/1416148.xml">
licensee</link>, Link International. <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://vogue.co.uk/vogue_daily/story/story.asp?stid=45693&amp;date=&amp;sid=#">
